        {
          "type": "ai-bubble",
          "text": "Kinetic energy refers to the energy an object possesses due to its motion. It is defined as the work needed to accelerate a body from rest to a given velocity. The formula for calculating kinetic energy is:\n\n\\[\nKE = \\frac{1}{2}mv^2\n\\]\n\nwhere:\n- \\( KE \\) is the kinetic energy,\n- \\( m \\) is the mass of the object,\n- \\( v \\) is its velocity.\n\nExamples of objects with different masses and velocities illustrate how kinetic energy varies:\n\n1. A heavy car moving quickly (\\( m = 5000 \\, \\text{kg}, v = 60 \\, \\text{m/s} \\)) has significant kinetic energy.\n2. A light bike moving slowly (\\( m = 10 \\, \\text{kg}, v = 3 \\, \\text{m/s} \\)) has less kinetic energy.\n\nIf an object is not moving (\\( v = 0 \\)), its kinetic energy is zero because there is no work done to accelerate it from rest.",
